                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>313 W 45th St.<lb/>
                N.Y. Aug 22d 1879.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr. Morais&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I enclose you<lb/> Rubenstein&#39;s latest.  He has<lb/> taken the idea of a Cincinnati<lb/> edition of the &#91;Hebrew&#93; in earnest&#44;<lb/> this quibble about &#91;Hebrew&#93; is<lb/> laughable.  I did not publish<lb/> it&#44; so I replied to him by<lb/> note&#44; because it dealt with<lb/> the editor&#44; rather than the<lb/> accuracy of the translation.<lb/></p>
            <p>I feel very much<lb/> inclined to print parallel<lb/> passages of the 2 translations&#45;&#45;<lb/> the length of yours is 12 columns<lb/> &#38; his 3.  Only I don&#39;t want<lb/> to engage in a lengthy<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>controversy&#8212;of no interest to<lb/> our readers.  I know Wise<lb/> is behind the whole affair&#58;<lb/> You may recollect<lb/> Raphall&#39;s answer to<lb/> W&#39;s views on the same subject.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have not seen this<lb/> week&#39;s <hi rend="underline">Record</hi>&#44; possibly<lb/> we have handled him<lb/> there.  He has turned his<lb/> Talmud training to good account.<lb/>  America will be a Garden<lb/> of Eden in five years&#33;&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours&#44;<lb/>
                Abr Isaac<lb/>
                Rev. S. Morais.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>The Resurrection.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;A few weeks ago&#44; there appeared in the<lb/> ISRAELITE an avowed translation of Mai&#45;<lb/>monides&#39; &#34;Treatise on the Resurrection of<lb/> the Dead&#34; from the pen of Mr. Rubenstein&#44;<lb/> student at the Hebrew Union College&#44; who<lb/> received his Talmudic training in Europe.<lb/>  In 1859 Rev. S. Morais contributed to trans&#45;<lb/>lation of the same treatise to the <emph rend="italics">Messenger</emph>.<lb/>  On comparison we find Mr. Rubenstein&#39;s<lb/> &#34;rendering&#44;&#34; so widely different from Rev.<lb/> Mr. Morais&#39; as to give exactly Maimon&#45;<lb/>ides never wrote.  Assuredly some explana&#45;<lb/>tion is needed&#44; or we shall feel tempted to<lb/> class Mr. r. with Mr. Goldammer&#44; whose<lb/> &#34;translation&#34; of Luzzatto&#39;s Chaldaic Gram&#45;<lb/>mar was duly commented upon two years<lb/> ago in our columns.  Possibly Mr. Ruben&#45;<lb/>stein has a Cincinnati edition of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; and this may account for variations be&#45;<lb/>tween Morais&#39; version and his perversion.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>&#45;&#45;<emph rend="italics">Jewish Messenger Aug</emph>. 15<lb/></p>
            <p>The following card in answer to the above<lb/> editorial will appear in the next edition of<lb/> that journal&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>A CARD.<lb/></p>
            <p>To the editor of the &#34;Jewish Messenger.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>It was with mingled feelings of pleasure<lb/> and pain that I read an article in the last<lb/> number of your <emph rend="italics">Messenger</emph> concerning me<lb/> and my translation of Maimonides&#39; Resur&#45;<lb/>rection.  Pleasure to know that you had de&#45;<lb/>voted time to the reaning of it&#59; pain to think<lb/> that so wise &#91;&#63;&#93; a man should denounce it as<lb/> a perversion before examining the original.<lb/>  Have you any authoritative translation upon<lb/> which you base so valuable &#91;&#63;&#93; a criticism&#63;<lb/>  I would call your attention to &#34;the transla&#45;<lb/>tor&#39;s reply&#44;&#34; and an editorial which ap&#45;<lb/>peared in the ISRAELITE of August 15.  I am<lb/> of the opinion that these articles&#44; although<lb/> originally not intended for you&#44; fit you<lb/> exactly&#44; and by examining the references<lb/> there noted&#44; you may be induced to retract<lb/> your able &#91;&#63;&#93; remarks upon my translation.<lb/></p>
            <p>Possibly by giving you credit for that criti&#45;<lb/>cism I may be doing you injustice&#44; for the<lb/> <emph rend="italics">Record</emph> of the <emph rend="italics">previous</emph> week contains sub&#45;<lb/>stantially the same.<lb/></p>
            <p>You refer to a Cincinnati edition of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I may as well inform you that there is<lb/> not only no Cincinnati edition&#44; but no such<lb/> work in existence.  Would it not be more<lb/> useful and beneficial did you devote the<lb/> time required in classifying me with Rev.<lb/> Goldammer&#44; to a review of your Hebrew as<lb/> well as your criticisms.  For charity&#39;s sake&#44;<lb/> let me instruct you that the correct name of<lb/> the work you wish to refer to is<lb/></p>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>If you can translate the original I will<lb/> with pleasure loan you one of the oldest and<lb/> most authentic copies extant.<lb/></p>
            <p>ISAAC RUBENSTEIN.<lb/></p>
            <p>NOTE&#8212;The copy of the epistle in question<lb/> is published with AZEROTH THEMAN&#44; by<lb/> Basang&#44; 1725.<lb/></p>
        </body>
